    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that is a common source of confusion, but your loan is behaving exactly as it should. When you make a fixed monthly payment on a declining balance loan, the interest calculation prioritizes the remaining principal first, which means more of your payment goes toward interest in early months and less toward the principal itself. As the balance drops, the total interest charged each month decreases, but your fixed payment amount stays the same, so the extra money automatically accelerates the principal reduction once the interest portion shrinks. This is why the principal balance drops slowly at first and then speeds up as the loan matures.",
