      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to feel that way, as it is a classic example of how the \"interest drag\" works against you initially. Every single month, the interest calculation acts like a tax on your remaining balance, forcing a portion of your fixed payment to feed the debt rather than reducing it. Since you are paying the same amount regardless, the extra dollars you *should* have been using to chip away at the principal are instead siphoned off by the compounding interest until the balance gets small enough. Think of it as a mathematical hurdle where the \"cost of doing business\" is highest when you have the most to pay, making early progress feel painfully slow compared to the later stages where your payment becomes a bigger hammer against the debt.",
